= La sierra no baja

The comandancia's answer is the oldest one the mountain gives, and it is not defiance so much as a fact of physics: the sierra does not come down for an election, because the sierra was never in the election, because the whole reason the sierra exists is that the election was closed to the people who took it. Let the valley have its July. The war keeps its own calendar, which is measured not in sexenios but in the patience of the poor.

[? if ending = "guerra_larga" : And the war, held at strength, does what strong wars do when the country's attention passes: it endures. July comes and goes in the distant plazas; the columns hold their zones; the corridos add a verse about the ones who did not come down. The state, busy with its stolen election, cannot spare the battalions to finish a war that refuses to end — and the war, refusing, becomes the one thing the counted and the stolen ballots both leave unfinished. Somewhere in the sierra a young fighter who was born the year of Tlatelolco cleans a rifle, and waits, and the decade turns, and the mountain keeps its appointment for another generation to arrive and understand. ?]

[? if ending = "exterminio" : And the war, held past its strength out of a pride the manuals warned against, meets the end the manuals promised. With the country looking at its ballot, the state finishes, quietly and without witnesses, the work it could never do under scrutiny: the last zones swept, the last columns run to ground, the encirclement closed on a war too weak to break it and too proud to leave. There is no July for the sierra. There is only the older arithmetic, done in the dark, one camp at a time. ?]

- @fin_sierra: Fin.

@fin_sierra
